<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1883-03-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1883-03-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="399" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d399">
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Frelinghuysen</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Daggett</persName>.</hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No 19.]</seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-03-02"><hi rend="italic">March 2,
                                        1883</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your dispatch of the 12th ultimo, No.
                                49, reporting the peaceful crowning of the King and Queen of the
                                Hawaiian Islands at noon of that day has been received.</p>
                            <p>The present is a fitting occasion to express anew the assurances of
                                the good will we bear to the Hawaiian Government and people. We have
                                also especial pleasure in learning that, as reported in your No. 41
                                of the 10th ultimo, two of our national vessels arrived at Honolulu
                                in season for His Majesty’s coronation.</p>
                            <p>I am, sir, etc.,</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Fred’k T.
                                    Frelinghuysen.</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>